column28: added link to report in readme

Resolving a bug when remote node is behind a private network  Background :  getOrConnect method tries to open a connection to an address only once. It should never open a second connection to a member. To achieve that we are using the remote address of a connection as the source of truth. The remote address is the one in the member list for members.  If the member is using private-addresses on a closed network; the client can not use that address on its config to connect that member. So we have two addresses to define single member on the client side.  How bug happens:  When client is already connected to members; it could be the case that all connections are dropped temporarily. In that case; we trigger `doConnectToCandidateCluster` logic. It connects to a random address provided in the config. This one can use `public address` of the member.  In the meantime; we have a periodic task `ConnectToAllClusterMembersTask` that tries to connect to all members in the latest known memberlist. This one uses the remote address which is the  `private address`  Both of them uses `getOrConnect` and `doConnectToCandidateCluster` can open a second connection while a first one is already there. Note that some of our other services rely on single connection per member logic.  How to fix: 1. `uuid` will be used  as the source of truth. This means what we can not know the uuid of a connection before opening a connection first. We will allow opening connections paralelly from `doConnectToCandidateCluster` path. As soon as a response returned from the server(with uuid); we check if a connection is already there and close the new connection before putting it in `activeConnection`.  Periodic `ConnectToAllClusterMembersTask` will not try to connect an already connected member.And it will use `uuid` to decide that.  2. This two paths will not use same method `getOrConnect` to simplify the logic. One will based on address and the other only uuid to make the intent clear.  Test: I could not write a unit test because this requires an inaccessible private network behind a public address.

column28: Resolve infinite alarms every 15 seconds with email/exchange (android issue 31246)  Resolves issue with Email (and Exchange?) that caused an ALARM_RTC to be signaled every 15 seconds without ending (repeating alarm that was never properly stopped.)  The cause was a self-repeating alarm that wasn't being canceled (and service that should have cancelled it was destroyed before it got canceled.)  This was great for battery life (as long as you didn't want to use the phone unplugged.)  By replacing the self-repeating alarm with one that's manually re-set each iteration; the alarm will gracefully go away when the service does.  For a discussion on this issue (and the reason we might never see a fix from google on this); please see:  http://code.google.com/p/android/issues/detail?id=31246  Patch-set 2: remove excess debugging Log.d() Patch-set 3: 3rd time is a charm: fix an old comment to reflect new code  Signed-off-by: Gary D <garyd9@gmail.com> Change-Id: Ife1370ac51edcc5c48ece39d6e2dbc84d154deb4

Make sure to retrieve the most up to date version of the composer message (#713)  Each time text is added in the ckeditor; the ckeditor onchange event is triggered and the message property is updated with the ckeditor content. When using the suggester; when inserting a mention in the ckeditor content; it is done using innerHTML (jquery html() exactly); which does not trigger the ckeditor onchange event. Therefore when posting a message; if the latest thing inserted in the ckeditor is a mention; the message content is not up to date. This fix makes sure to get the most updated version of the message by using a reference to the exo-activity-rich-editor and calling its getMessage() method. This is not the best solution probably because its couples a bit the components and it means the v-model binding variable is not always up to date; but no solutin has been found to detect the change after the mention insertion.
